			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I saw that article too Jeal.
<br />

<br />
First of all it's from Reuters.  Everyday I'm becoming more convinced that Reuters isn't a trustworthy, unbiased source.  They don't even list the reporter doing the article.  No telling who it is, but we see the article loaded with opinion.  Opinions that sound almost bogus.
<br />

<br />
Let's examine this article and the fallacies it says.  You have to read between the lines.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Pot is no longer the gentle weed of the 1960s and may pose a greater threat than cocaine or even heroin because so many more people use it.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"> 
<br />

<br />
This part is the unknown writer's opinion.  No name, no face, just text.
<br />

<br />
Well if you base it solely on the number of users, of course pot will be more than cocaine and heroin combined.  And of course since it is ILLEGAL, it does pose a greater threat, if breaking the law is a threat.
<br />

<br />
Also note the word "gentle".  It was never gentle, but the writer tries to give that impression as if to trigger some emotional feeling that it's now dangerous and wasn't then.  All that in one sentence.  Good one.
<br />

<br />
John Walters, head of the White House Office of National Drug Control Policy says:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">If you told people that one in five of 12- to 17-year-olds who ever used marijuana in their lives need treatment, I don't think people would remotely understand it."</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Can you believe this?  Note the word NEED.  He is right though, I for one don't remotely understand where the hell he came up with this.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">According to the report, children and teenagers are three times more likely to be in treatment for marijuana abuse than for alcohol, and six times likelier to be in treatment for marijuana than for all other illegal drugs combined.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Interesting comment here and we should examine this.  This almost seems like a double-edged sword.  You can look at this many different ways...
<br />

<br />
1) Alcohol is legal - marijuana isn't, so therefore, criminalizing marijuana should make it harder to get.  It isn't as I pointed out earlier in this thread.
<br />

<br />
2) Since marijuana is illegal and alcohol isn't, are most kids forced to get treatment if they are caught with it by the law?  Or do they do so willingly?  I think the former applies.
<br />

<br />
3) Well I would imagine that most kids stay away from harder drugs either because of the difficulty getting it, the intelligence to know it's 10x more dangerous or the cost.  There are exceptions, but how many kids do you know that snort coke, shoot up heroin, drop acid or pop X?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">And it found the age of youths using marijuana is falling. The teenagers aged 12 to 17 said on average they started trying marijuana at 13 1/2. The same survey found that adults aged 18 to 25 had first tried it at 16.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Kids are getting younger and younger doing things that we wouldn't have dreamed of doing back then.  Hell girls today are having sex and gettting pregnant barely out of puberty.
<br />

<br />
That statement means jack in my book, but of course it sounds like there's a problem.  Of course there's a problem, kids are doing things, lots of things at a younger age and marijuana is only one of those things.  Of course numbers are easy to juggle and unassociate with other data that would counter it.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">"We shouldn't be victims of reefer madness," he said, referring to the 1930s propaganda film "Reefer Madness" that became a 1970s cult classic for its over-the-top scenes of marijuana turning teenagers into homicidal maniacs.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
And we shouldn't be victims of anti-marijuana propaganda.
<br />

<br />
You can either look at marijuana being used more by kids and at a younger age as a problem.
<br />

<br />
But should we try and throw more tax dollars to stop it or make it legal and control it?
<br />

<br />
We are in a deficit crisis and throwing money away at a hopeless cause is not the way to go.<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=140009" target="_blank" class="postlink"><span style="font-size: 14px; line-height: normal"><span style="color: green"><span style="font-weight: bold">Ozzone</span></span></span></a>
