			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I am all for leagizing marijuana.
<br />

<br />
I don't not smoke at al,l marijuana or tabaco. But this is my personal choice. If you are of age I believe you should be educated in the risks of your choices and if you in your actions are not harming somone else then it should be your choice and be permitted to do what you will to yourself.
<br />

<br />
I remember watching an interesting documenty quite a few years back by Dr David Suziki. He trided to look at different cultures and how they delt with drug usage. One of the big contrasts was between America and Holland. America (yes and to a lesser extent Australia) treats people who take drugs as criminals and say that drugs are evil and a problem. Holland thakes the other extreme and many drugs are legalized or de-criminilized. They say it is people with problems that take drugs.  Interestingly there is a higher usage of drugs in countries like America and Australia where it is seen as illegal than a country like Holland.
<br />

<br />
The other thing about the drug depate is the problems caused by perscription drugs. These are legal there is greatly reduced social stigma from being addicted or to taking these drugs but they can cause many social and biological problems. 
<br />

<br />
Here in Australia a majority of states have de-criminilised the use of Marijuana if not made it legal. States such as South Australia allow upto 5 plants per person to be grown in your back yard. It has been de-criminilised but it is illegal to sell Marijuana and as such if you are caught dealing you go to jail.
<br />

<br />
Usage has not increased if anything is has dropped. Also the social stigma has to some extent been removed so those people that wish to seek help for issues they have with drugs can be addressed more readly. 
<br />

<br />
As to marijuana being a gateway drug in some circimstances this maybe the case, but not so in mine. When I was about 21 I went though a really tough time and turned to drugs. The frist drug I ever took was speed.  It would be easier for me list the drugs I have not taken than the ones I have. Here in Queenlsand (the state I live in) all drugs incuding marijuana are illegal. After a few years I addressed my problems and have not taken drugs since. It has now been 8 years. Drugs being illegal did not stop me from being able to obtain. It was VERY easy. The concerns I had were that thought it was my choice I was not able to gurantee the quality or purity of the drugs being supplied.
<br />

<br />
Legilization of drugs and by this I mean all drugs. Would allow the people that make the life choice to take these substances to ensure the quality of what they chose to put in their bodies and to seek help if they chose to stop their habit. 
<br />

<br />
All drugs in general taken to excess are harmful, this includes alcohol, taboco and currently illicid substances. However if people chose to take their drug of choice it will always be avaliable, legal or not. 
<br />

<br />
Take the money used for trying and jailing people who take drugs, put it into drug education treat the people for the reasons they turn to drugs (if they wish to be treated),  treat them like human beings and not criminals and I am sure there will be reduced drug issues including organised crime, and social ramifications.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
